[1
Date: Mon 26 Feb 2001 07:09:56 -0500
From: Patricia Doyle, PhD <dr_p_doyle@hotmail.com>
Source: South China Morning Press (Hong Kong), AP Report, Mon 26 Feb 2001
[edited
<http://thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?file=/2001/2/26/nation/2603sbnu&sec=nat>

Encephalitis Death in Negri Sembilan Causes Alarm
-------------------------------------------------
SEREMBAN: The Negri Sembilan Health Department has sent blood specimens
from a worker from Bukit Pelanduk who died of encephalitis to University
Hospital for testing. Its director, Datuk Dr. Ahmad Razin Ahmad Mahir, said
a post-mortem had been conducted on the deceased worker and it showed that
he had died of encephalitis. "But we do not know the cause of the
encephalitis, whether it is caused by Japanese Encephalitis (JE) virus,
Nipah virus or some other virus," he said yesterday. The department was
waiting for the results which were expected to be ready in 2 weeks' time.
The patient was admitted to a hospital here on 26 Jan 2001 and died 3 days
later after he lapsed into a coma. "So far, there is no new reported case
of JE virus or Nipah virus from Bukit Pelanduk," he said.
Bukit Pelanduk residents were evacuated 2 years ago following the Japanese
encephalitis virus/Nipah virus outbreak that killed more than 100 people.
Dr. Razin explained that the victim had shown symptoms of encephalitis
during the height of that outbreak. He added that the victim had been
involved in the pig-culling exercise during that outbreak. MCA Assemblyman
Datuk Lee Yuen Fong, who was the Lukut Operations Centre Chief during the
outbreak, yesterday urged people to contact the health department
immediately if they knew of anyone who showed signs of the disease.
[byline: Hah Foong Lian
--
Patricia A. Doyle, PhD
<dr_p_doyle@hotmail.com>
